{"key":"processedPost-11872106","value":{"id":11872106,"first":11868597,"last":12280977,"when":1264102919,"utime":"01/21/10 09:41 PM","cleanedPost":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><strong>Trim said:</strong><br />Actually, it's been shown that temps of around 83 are perfect. Since the jars make their own heat, you only need about 78-80 degree temps. (Something close to that atleast.) An ambient temp of 86 would unecessarily risk contamination.</blockquote><br />83F is not going to produce the fastest growth.&nbsp; Mycelium slows down at any temp of 83 and above.&nbsp; Considering that glass is an insulator, the temperature inside the jars is at least a few degrees warmer.&nbsp; The old figure of fastest growth at a <i>mycelium temperature</i>, not ambient, of 86 is flat out wrong.<br />Perhaps fastest growth for pf jars is an ambient temp of around 75f to 80F, but higher temps also stimulate bacteria and thermophilic molds.&nbsp; In my mushroom farm, success on every substrate counts more than getting colonized a day or two sooner, so I follow the standard incubation temperature of 69F used by the big commercial mushroom farms, and it works perfectly.<br />RR"}}